esex, England","Wales":"Wales","England":"England"},"nl":{"1180–1265":"1180–1265","1176–Male":"1176–Overleden","1185–1236":"1185–1236","1235–1295":"1235–1295","1160–1205":"1160–1205","1169–1205":"1169–1205","1205":"1205","after 1205":"na 1205","1236":"1236","1235":"1235","1169":"1169","1265":"1265","1176":"1176","1295":"1295","1185":"1185","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","Ollantigh Manor, Ollantigh, Wye, Ashford, Kent, England":"Wye, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","London, Surrey, England":"London England Temple, Newchapel, Surrey, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Wales":"Wales","England":"England"},"en":{"1180–1265":"1180–1265","1176–Male":"1176–Deceased","1185–1236":"1185–1236","1235–1295":"1235–1295","1160–1205":"1160–1205","1169–1205":"1169–1205","1205":"1205","after 1205":"after 1205","1236":"1236","1235":"1235","1169":"1169","1265":"1265","1176":"1176","1295":"1295","1185":"1185","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","Ollantigh Manor, Ollantigh, Wye, Ashford, Kent, England":"Wye, Kent, England, United Kingdom","London, Surrey, England":"London England Temple, Newchapel, Surrey, England, United Kingdom","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Wales":"Wales","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"DECAMPO","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Galician: variant of   Ocampo  , with fused preposition <i>d(e)</i> ‘from’. Compare   De Ocampo  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ocampo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Juan, Roberto, Luis, Francisco, Jesus, Manuel, Pedro, Jorge, Armando, Cesar.","Galician: topographic name meaning ‘the field’, from the definite article <i>o</i> (masculine singular) + <i>campo</i> ‘field’ (from Latin <i>campus</i>); or a habitational name from a town of this name in Lugo province, Galicia (Spain). Compare   De Ocampo   and   Docampo  ."]},{"name":"De Ocampo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Roberto, Eduardo, Jose, Marina, Alberto, Anacleto, Angelita, Augusto, Bonifacio, Edgardo, Edmundo, Efrain.","Spanish: altered form of Galician   Docampo   or a variant of   Ocampo   ‘the field’, with the preposition <i>de</i> ‘from’. This surname is most common in the Philippines, where it is also spelled <b>Deocampo</b>."]}]},{"name":"Rodger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."],"variants":[{"name":"Roger","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."]}]},{"name":"Norman","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Germanic origin, from <i>nord</i> ‘north’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’, i.e. ‘Norseman’. This name was in use in England before the Conquest, and was reinforced by its use among the Norman invaders themselves. The Normans were the inhabitants of Normandy in northern France, whose name is a reference to the Vikings who took control of the region in the 9th century. In the 11th and 12th centuries they achieved remarkable conquests, including not only Britain but also Sicily, southern Italy, and Antioch. In the Scottish Highlands it is used as the Anglicized equivalent of Tormod ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Rodger Norman DECAMPO was born in 1180, in Wales, his father, Cedrick Decampo, was 20 and his mother, Celda, was 11. He married Feona. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1265, in London England Temple, Newchapel, Surrey, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 85."},"et":{"1180–1265":"1180–1265","1176–Male":"1176–Surnud","1185–1236":"1185–1236","1235–1295":"1235–1295","1160–1205":"1160–1205","1169–1205":"1169–1205","1205":"1205","after 1205":"pärast 1205","1236":"1236","1235":"1235","1169":"1169","1265":"1265","1176":"1176","1295":"1295","1185":"1185","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","Ollantigh Manor, Ollantigh, Wye, Ashford, Kent, England":"Wye, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","London, Surrey, England":"London England Temple, Newchapel, Surrey, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Wales":"Wales","England":"England"},"fi":{"1180–1265":"1180–1265","1176–Male":"1176–Kuollut","1185–1236":"1185–1236","1235–1295":"1235–1295","1160–1205":"1160–1205","1169–1205":"1169–1205","1205":"1205","after 1205":"1205 jälkeen","1236":"1236","1235":"1235","1169":"1169","1265":"1265","1176":"1176","1295":"1295","1185":"1185","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","Ollantigh Manor, Ollantigh, Wye, Ashford, Kent, England":"Wye, Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","London, Surrey, England":"London England Temple, Newchapel, Surrey, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Wales":"Wales","England":"England"},"fr":{"1180–1265":"1180–1265","1176–Male":"1176–Décédé","1185–1236":"1185–1236","1235–1295":"1235–1295","1160–1205":"1160–1205","1169–1205":"1169–1205","1205":"1205","after 1205":"après 1205","1236":"1236","1235":"1235","1169":"1169","1265":"1265","1176":"1176","1295":"1295","1185":"1185","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","Ollantigh Manor, Ollantigh, Wye, Ashford, Kent, England":"Wye, Kent, Angleterre, Royaum